nRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/F9FBB412-675C-4E25-A02B-FBEE1AB62509"><gtr:id>F9FBB412-675C-4E25-A02B-FBEE1AB62509</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Michael</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Murdoch</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Barrow</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI001387%2F1"><gtr:id>6D971DB3-2808-4D7C-BB9B-CF4F64623AB6</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding value for money in local authority led public services: what it is and what drives it and how can it be measured?</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I001387/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The aim of this research is to review aspects of the existing value for money (VFM) methodology used to evaluate the delivery of local public services and to examine some particularly policy initiatives in the light of VFM considerations. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This is of current interest for two main reasons:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>The shift towards a more area-based system of provision of local services. &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>The forthcoming reductions in levels of public expenditure. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>The research intends to focus more upon the processes of VFM evaluation (eg institutional arrangements, how users make use of indicators, etc) rather than examine the technical details of how one measures VFM, as this latter topic has been well researched already. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>A review of the current methodology will look for gaps in the current framework, eg how does one evaluate policies that are intended to change people's preferences? In addition, the research will look at other concepts, such as empowerment of users, and how this might affect VFM. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The results of the research should improve our understanding of what drives VFM and how policy interventions can be made more effective in achieving the goal of value for money. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>48739</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>LARIA conference presentation</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>53610D62-409A-4758-8D5A-2EF6F6699834</gtr:id><gtr:impact>My presentation covered work I did while at DCLG, making use of a dataset (the Place Survey) to investigate citizens' awareness of value for money offered by their local authority. Discussion of the paper followed the presentation.

